Extracting String Parts :
The are Three Methods for extracting part of string :
1.slice(start , end)
2.substring(start , end)
3.substr(start , length)


1. The slice() Method
   slice() extracts a part of a string and returns the extracted part in a new string.
   The method takes 2 parameters: the starting index (position), and the ending index (position).

Example : var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
          var res = str.slice(7, 13);

1.1 If a parameter is negative, the position is counted from the end of the string.
    This example slices out a portion of a string from position -12 to position -6:

Example  : var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
           var res = str.slice(-12,-6);

1.2 If you omit the second parameter, the method will slice out the rest of the string

Example : var res = str.slice(7);

2. The substring() Method
   substring() is similar to slice().
   The difference is that substring() cannot accept negative indexes.

Example : var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
          var res = str.substring(7, 13);
          Output : Banana

note : If you omit the second parameter, substring() will slice out the rest of the string.

3. The substr() Method
   substr() is similar to slice().

   The difference is that the second parameter specifies the length of the extracted part.

Example : var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
          var res = str.substr(7, 6);
          output : Banana

note : If the first parameter is negative, the position counts from the end of the string.
       The second parameter can not be negative, because it defines the length.
       If you omit the second parameter, substr() will slice out the rest of the string.






